<HEADLINE>
<P>
COMMUNITY NEWS: HAWTHORNE; OFFICIALS REVISE LAW ON ADULT BUSINESSES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The City Council approved an ordinance Monday aimed at regulating adult 
businesses while protecting First Amendment rights to free speech.  
</P>
<P>
 In a 3-0 vote, the council passed the law that allows the city to determine 
when, how and where adult businesses operate but not what they sell, said City 
Atty.Glen Shishito. 
</P>
<P>
 "These businesses are afforded First Amendment protection," Shishito said. "If 
we don't follow the law, we're open to liability."  
</P>
<P>
 Council members Steven Andersen, Martha Bails and Betty J. Ainsworth voted for 
the measure. Councilwoman Ginny M. Lambert abstained and Mayor Larry Guidi was 
absent. 
</P>
<P>
 The city's previous rules on adult businesses were vague and could be used to 
regulate what materials were sold -- in violation of the First Amendment, 
Shishito said. 
</P>
<P>
 The new law requires new adult businesses to pass a checklist of standards 
that regulate the time and manner of conducting business, including the hours 
of operation and public display of adult materials. 
</P>
<P>
 "We can't put them out of business," Andersen said. "This is about as much as 
we can do." 
</P>
<P>
 City officials are also changing the zoning codes to restrict adult businesses 
to certain parts of the city. 
</P>
<P>
 Lambert said she abstained as a protest against adult businesses: "I object 
strongly to that type of business in my community." 
</P>
</TEXT>
