<HEADLINE>
<P>
GARDEN FRESH; THEY CALL IT MELON YELLOW 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By SYLVIA THOMPSON 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Does yellow watermelon taste richer than red? To me it does. Golden foods seem 
to have golden flavor. Butterscotch. Peaches, nectarines, papayas, pineapple. 
Buttery crookneck -- and acorn, banana and spaghetti squashes. Corn and wax 
beans. Some tomatoes, melons and plums. The sunny side of an egg. Olive oil 
from Provence. 
</P>
<P>
 Does home-grown watermelon taste better than store-bought? You bet! Cutting 
into a golden watermelon you've raised is downright thrilling. 
</P>
<P>
 Watermelons have been giving pleasure for thousands of years. For their part, 
the melons enjoy the hot days and nights of summer with the softness of 
humidity in the air. 
</P>
<P>
 Seeds are sown indoors in spring. Order early. From seed to table, big 
watermelons take about 3 1/2 months. If you're in a warm-to-hot-summer part of 
Southern California, sow directly into the soil from April through June. Along 
the coast, sow May and June. In the high desert, mid-March through June; in the 
low desert, February and March. In the mountains, where I live, we start 
watermelon seeds indoors in May.  
</P>
<P>
 Willhite Seed Co. in Poolville, Tex., offers a mouthwatering assortment of 
goldens. Willhite says farmers grow Orangeglo for themselves (in catalogue 
descriptions, "a fine home garden variety" means the rind is too thin to ship 
without breaking, so grow it for your own pleasure). Orangeglo's flesh is the 
color of ripe peaches, and the oval fruits can weigh 50 pounds.  
</P>
<P>
 Tastigold is a round golden watermelon half Orangeglo's weight. Picked at the 
peak of ripeness, Tastigold's flavor rivals the best watermelon of any color. 
For an open-pollinated melon -- you can save its seeds and grow them -- choose 
sugary crisp Golden Honey. 
</P>
<P>
 In inland areas where citrus thrives, you can grow any golden watermelon 
cultivar you like, but in warm areas where water is in short supply, plant 
sweet Desert King. I have, and it's not only delicious but enormously 
drought-tolerant. In cooler arid climates such as the high desert, try Hopi 
Yellow Meated, which is grown in the sandy Southwest on nothing but rain water. 
I've grown that one too, and it's exciting. Both are open-pollinated. 
</P>
<P>
 Where summers are cooler or the seasons shorter, choose small icebox-size 
melons that ripen in 70 to 75 days. You can rely on Yellow Baby to yield sweet 
seven-inch golden watermelons with few seeds. Sunshine F1 is slightly larger, 
with crisp, juicy flesh and thick rind for pickling. Delicious Early Moonbeam 
is open-pollinated. Yellow Doll, a small, very sweet hybrid with thin rind, 
ripens earliest, about 68 days. 
</P>
<P>
 To germinate seeds, wrap them in moist paper towels and seal in a plastic bag. 
Keep the bag at 75 to 85 degrees. Check every day to make sure the towel is 
moist. It takes five to 10 days for the seeds to sprout. 
</P>
<P>
 Watermelons need warm soil, so the day you sow your seeds, get a jump on the 
season: For each plant, lay a four- to five-foot square of black plastic mulch 
on a patch in full sun -- a southern exposure is best. The soil must be light, 
loose, well-draining, super-rich in organic matter and slightly acid (a pH of 6 
to 6.5). 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 When your seeds have sprouted, set two of them 1/4-inch deep in a three-inch 
container of good potting mix in a paper or peat pot. Grow in bright light at 
75 degrees and never let the soil dry out. When they are a couple of inches 
tall, pinch off the weaker of the two. 
</P>
<P>
 When the weather has settled and the soil is warm, slit an opening in the 
plastic mulch (where there's frost, wait until the last frost is a couple of 
weeks behind you). Carefully pull away the pot from the seedling and set the 
plant in the ground (mustn't disturb the roots). Space bush cultivars -- the 
ones that mature fastest -- about 3 feet apart. Water thoroughly with a Vitamin 
B1 solution.  
</P>
<P>
 If the nights are sometimes chilly, cover the seedlings with a floating row 
cover (a sheltering veil that lets sun and water through), but remove it when 
the nights turn warm or when the first flowers appear. If it's a cool spring, 
leave the plastic mulch in place until the days get hot, then remove it. 
Replace with a mulch of straw or leaves kept a few inches away from the vine. 
</P>
<P>
 Water every four days until fruits are developing; after that, once a week 
give an inch of water. Always water before 3 p.m., using a drip system if 
possible. Once a month, in the morning, spray leaves with a solution of half 
liquid fish, half kelp. Pick off any bugs. Around the middle of September, 
pinch off all blossoms -- this permits the plant to throw its energy into 
ripening existing fruit. 
</P>
<P>
 You don't have to plant watermelons in a traditional watermelon patch. A bush 
watermelon looks charming in a garden border. The leaves resemble large, 
elongated maple leaves -- sometimes they're speckled white or gold. If there's 
room in your border for a vine to trail along the ground, remember -- the 
best-flavored melons come from long vines.  
</P>
<P>
 A better idea is to train long vines up a fence or trellis. In good soil, 
these can be set a foot apart. Growing watermelons upward is a great idea. Just 
support the fruits with a sling of soft cotton. If you haven't got room for a 
watermelon in the garden, raise a bush cultivar in a large growing bag on the 
deck or patio. Inquire about the bags at a nursery. 
</P>
<P>
 What's a golden sound of summer? The hollow punk ! that comes when you thump a 
ripe watermelon. While not a trustworthy test at the market (overripe 
watermelons can punk too), thump your growing watermelons every few days. Do 
this in the morning when the melons are coolest. Other tests: The curly tendril 
on the stalk closest to the melon has dried, and the spot on the melon where it 
touches the ground is sunny yellow. Fruits generally keep in the peak of 
ripeness 10 to 14 days. 
</P>
<P>
 Harvest your melon with a knife, taking an inch of stem. Store it in a cool 
place. Thick rind of unripe melons can also be pickled. 
</P>
<P>
 Watermelon is one of Mother Nature's perfections. Unlike bananas and 
raspberries (which need cream), apples and pears (which need cheese), or 
peaches and strawberries (which need powdered sugar), there's nothing that 
watermelon needs to make it better -- and to me, golden watermelon is the pick 
of the crop. SOURCES 
</P>
<P>
 * Fresh: Often at farmers markets. 
</P>
<P>
 * Seeds: Desert King, Orangeglo and Tastigold from Willhite Seed Co., 
Poolville, Tex. 76076. 
</P>
<P>
 Early Moonbeam from Seeds of Change, Box 15700, Santa Fe, N.M. 87506-5700. 
</P>
<P>
 Golden Honey and Yellow Doll from Porter & Son, Box 104, Stephenville, Tex. 
76401-0104. 
</P>
<P>
 Hopi Yellow Meated from Native Seeds/SEARCH, 2509 N. Campbell Ave., No. 325, 
Tucson, Ariz. 85719. 
</P>
<P>
 Sunshine F1 and floating row cover from Johnny's, Foss Hill Road, Albion, Me. 
04910-9731. 
</P>
<P>
 Yellow Baby from Stokes, Box 548, Buffalo, N.Y. 14240-0548. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Wanting something handsome and unusual to serve friends for lunch, I put 
together an Asian sort of golden watermelon salad. Colors and shapes are 
delightful, and all the elements work beautifully together -- the warm-flavored 
sesame oil and sweet rice vinegar are the catalysts. A mouthful of watermelon 
and snow peas is a pleasing surprise. All except the noodles (which may soon go 
limp) can be prepared a few hours in advance . If a composed salad isn't your 
cup of tea, cut the watermelon into large-bite-size chunks and toss all the 
ingredients together -- it'll be a different kind of gorgeous. And of course 
the recipe works with red-fleshed melon as well. Offer a fruity white wine such 
as Sauvignon Blanc. For dessert, serve slices of sponge cake garnished with 
sprigs of mint.  
</P>
<P>
 SALAD OF GOLDEN WATERMELON, SNOW PEAS AND SHRIMP 1 pound snow peas 3 pounds 
golden watermelon Mild vegetable oil 2 ounces cellophane noodles (mung bean 
flour noodles) 2 large bunches watercress, leaves and tender stems, chilled 32 
large shrimp, tails intact (about 3/4 pound), cooked 4 rings sliced from small 
sweet red pepper, chilled 2 tablespoons Asian sesame oil 1/4 cup rice vinegar 
Salt, freshly ground white pepper to taste 
</P>
<P>
 Remove strings from fresh snow peas. Drop into large pot boiling salted water. 
After 30 seconds when tender-crisp -- scoop out and drop into ice water. When 
cold, drain. Pat dry, wrap and chill. 
</P>
<P>
 Cut watermelon into wedges. Remove rind. Slice watermelon 1/2-inch thick, then 
cut into 32 long triangles. Wrap and chill. 
</P>
<P>
 In large heavy skillet over medium-high heat, bring 1/4-inch oil to 340 
degrees (an inch-wide bread cube browns in 70 seconds). Fry noodles by small 
handfuls. Once expanded, turn with tongs. Lift out before color deepens and 
drain on absorbent paper. 
</P>
<P>
 To serve, cover chilled plates with watercress. On each, arrange 8 pieces 
watermelon as spokes of wheel. Set 1 shrimp at wide edge of each watermelon 
wedge, tails pointing in same direction. Overlap pea pods in center in mound. 
Crown pods with pepper ring, then strew noodles over all. Blend sesame oil, 
vinegar, salt and pepper and dribble over salad. Taste for seasoning. Makes 4 
servings. 
</P>
<P>
 Each serving contains about: 
</P>
<P>
 447 calories; 218 mg sodium; 129 mg cholesterol; 24 grams fat; 39 grams 
carbohydrates; 22 grams protein; 3.85 grams fiber. 
</P>
</TEXT>
