<HEADLINE>
<P>
CITY HALL JOURNAL: LONG BEACH; COUNCIL TO WEIGH BAN ON ROADSIDE SOLICITORS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JOHN POPE 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The City Council has voted unanimously to consider a proposal that would ban 
people from asking motorists for work or money at street corners. 
</P>
<P>
 The proposal was introduced by Councilman Douglas S. Drummond, who said that 
solicitors often create traffic problems at busy intersections in the city's 
east side.The ordinance would also apply to people selling items such as 
flowers or fruit at intersections, he said. 
</P>
<P>
 "It's a roadway situation that impedes traffic and creates danger for the 
person soliciting and the drivers," he said. 
</P>
<P>
 Drummond said a similar ordinance in the city of Agoura Hills has survived 
court challenges because it bans solicitations at intersections but does not 
outlaw them entirely.  
</P>
<P>
 Marshall Blesofsky, treasurer of an advocacy group called the Homeless 
Organizing Committee, said the proposal is an infringement on free speech that 
unfairly targets the city's homeless. "The First Amendment guarantees certain 
rights, and that includes the right to hold a 'Will work for food,' sign," he 
said. JOHN POPE 
</P>
</TEXT>
