<HEADLINE>
<P>
SCIENTISTS DIG UP TUSK OF PYGMY MAMMOTH; ARCHEOLOGY: TOOTH IS PART OF FOSSIL 
FOUND ON SANTA ROSA ISLAND THAT IS BELIEVED TO BE MOST COMPLETE SKELETON OF 
CREATURE EVER FOUND. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By PHYLLIS W. JORDAN, SPECIAL TO THE TIMES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 After hours of excavating a rare pygmy mammoth fossil, archeologist Don Morris 
scrambled up a steep, sandy cliff and broke the news to a colleague Wednesday 
morning. 
</P>
<P>
 "We've got a tusk down there," Morris said breathlessly. "It's really nifty. 
It's all in the sand, and it's in terrific shape." 
</P>
<P>
 Sure enough, the prehistoric skeleton discovered earlier this summer on Santa 
Rosa Island came complete with a 25-inch-long tusk, gleaming like polished wood 
in the bright, noonday sun. 
</P>
<P>
 The fossil is believed to be the most complete skeleton ever found of the 
mammoth that often grew no larger than a Saint Bernard. 
</P>
<P>
 This particular creature stood about 3 1/2 feet high at the shoulder, weighed 
as much as 500 pounds and lived as long as 75,000 years ago, scientists 
estimated after their first day of excavation. 
</P>
<P>
 A team of scientists from across the nation began digging at the site Tuesday 
and, by Wednesday, had already discovered key portions of the ancestral 
elephant's frame. 
</P>
<P>
 Carefully, two scientists used dental picks to scrape sand from the mammoth's 
pelvis bone, which could hold the answer to the animal's gender. 
</P>
<P>
 A biologist cleared sediment from the mammoth's eye socket with a trowel and 
brushed sand off the bridge of its nose. 
</P>
<P>
 The spine's jagged edge, bleached white from exposure, stuck out sharply from 
the eroding sand dune. 
</P>
<P>
 It was the spine that first drew a San Diego geologist to the fossil in June. 
Without that chance discovery, the rare skeleton could have been lost to 
exposure or to the sea, which is slowly eating away the aqua blue cove barely 
100 feet from the dune. 
</P>
<P>
 "It's the luck of science," said Morris, archeologist for the Channel Islands 
Park Service. 
</P>
<P>
 The location of the fossil, mostly held in loose sand, is also a stroke of 
luck. 
</P>
<P>
 "This sand is like going through butter with a hot knife," said Larry 
Agenbroad, a paleontologist who studies mammoths at Northern Arizona University 
and the Mammoth Site in South Dakota. "I'm used to sand, but much more cemented 
sand." 
</P>
<P>
 The downside is that the steep slope makes it impossible to bring heavy 
equipment to the site. The digging is all done by hand. 
</P>
<P>
 "That's the only way to do it," Agenbroad said. "Any machinery down here would 
already be in the ocean." 
</P>
<P>
 Indeed, every step on the eroding dune sends showers of sand down the hill. A 
bright orange safety fence is all that separates the scientists and their 
equipment from a sea cliff and the surf below. 
</P>
<P>
 Agenbroad speculated that the mammoth may have died in a landslide that 
covered it with sand. But whatever the cause of death, scientists believe the 
body was quickly buried in sand, initially sparing it from erosion and 
deterioration. 
</P>
<P>
 About 2,000 years ago, they estimate, a gully or arroyo developed, and water 
began running down the dune onto the mammoth fossil. 
</P>
<P>
 Tom Rockwell, a geologist from San Diego State University, pointed to a darker 
spot on the sand behind the fossil, indicating the path of the gully. 
</P>
<P>
 The water eroded one of the tusks and some of the bones. Agenbroad projects 
that the skeleton is still 75% to 85% intact. Scientists have found some 
fragments, including a piece of shoulder blade the size of a dinner plate, 
farther down the dune. 
</P>
<P>
 But the big discovery, thus far, has been the tusk. The two-foot, extended 
tooth, made of the same substance as human teeth, survived for eons virtually 
intact. 
</P>
<P>
 Agenbroad has found nearly 100 tusks in a South Dakota sinkhole called the 
Mammoth Site, but has never excavated a pygmy mammoth. Wednesday, he rubbed his 
hand against the tusk's smooth surface, feeling the bevels at the tip. 
</P>
<P>
 From the tusk, Agenbroad began to speculate about the mammoth buried in the 
sand dune. He believes the animal was a male, about 40 years old. He also 
believes the pygmy variety descended from the Columbian mammoth, which he has 
found in South Dakota. 
</P>
<P>
 At some point, mammoths swam to the Channel Islands, which were once one land 
mass lying about three to four miles off shore. After generations in the 
secluded spot, the species began to shrink -- an evolutionary process common in 
island mammals. 
</P>
<P>
 The real analysis, including a final estimate on the age of the bones, will 
come after months of study. Right now, the excavation team hopes to complete 
its dig by Aug. 19. 
</P>
<P>
 The discovery has produced a flurry of interest in the islands. Channel 
Islands Aviation has already filled three plane trips to view the excavation 
site and is filling up a fourth trip set for next Wednesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
