<HEADLINE>
<P>
RUSSIA, MOLDOVA AGREE ON TROOP WITHDRAWAL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Reuters 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Russia and Moldova said Wednesday that they have agreed on a three-year 
timetable for the withdrawal of an estimated 15,000 Russian troops from the 
former Soviet republic. 
</P>
<P>
 Negotiators who initialed the draft agreement told a news conference here in 
the Moldovan capital that the deal will take effect as soon as the two 
governments approve the text and their leaders sign it. 
</P>
<P>
 The Moldovan deputy foreign minister, Nicolae Osmochescu, said the government 
agreed to the timetable -- longer than it initially wanted -- because military 
experts said this was the minimum period needed to withdraw the Russian troops' 
huge stockpiles of weapons and ammunition. 
</P>
</TEXT>
